A solar cell junction is basically characterized by two parameters, its selectivity and its passivation. The selectivity is given by the potential barrier for one type of charge carriers. In a heterojunction this barrier consists of the build-in potential ψbi, the difference between the Fermi level position in the two semiconductors, and additionally the band offset ΔEc (cf. Fig. 3). The passivation is characterized by the surface recombination velocity vS at the metal front electrode and, in heterojunctions more importantly, the interface recombination velocity vI. This leads to the following contribution of the junction to the dark recombination current density J0 of the heterojunction solar cell:2J0≈qNDvIexp(qψbikT)+qNDvSexp(q(ψbi+ΔEC)kT).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
